		<div id="comment_body_64504207"><p><div class="quote"><p>Number of registered cars in the U.S: about 300,000,000<br>Number of gas stations in the U.S.: about 150,000<br>So, one station for every 2,000 registered cars.<br>Let's be generous and give each station 20 pumps.<br>So one pump for every 100 registered cars.<br>1 public charger for every 20 electric cars is starting to sound pretty good.<br>Especially when you compare filling a gas tank at home to charging an EV at home.<br>(Registered car and gas station estimates from googling.)</p></div><p>okay, well 20 pumps * 150000 stations = 3,000,000 pumps<br>Each pump can refuel a car in ~5 minutes, so ~12 cars/hour, ~288cars/day.<br>288 * 3,000,000 = 864,000,000 cars/day</p><p>So we have capacity to refuel 864 million cars/day.  Even if stations are only open 8 hours<nobr> <wbr></nobr>/day that's 288 million</p><p>Now lets do public chargers. According to: <a href="https://cleantechnica.com/2023/04/25/how-many-dc-fast-chargers-are-needed-in-usa/" title="cleantechnica.com">https://cleantechnica.com/2023...<span class="substr"> </span></a> [cleantechnica.com] <br>"The U.S. Department of Energy said that there were around 140,000 EV charging ports in the country at the end of last year, up from roughly 53,000 individ</p></div>
